The article discusses President Obama's proposed measures to prepare American children for success in college and the workforce. The President is proposing changes to the Elementary and Secondary Education Act to help states transition and implement college and career readiness standards. These changes include high-quality assessments, improvements to teaching, and teacher preparation and development. The article also highlights the collaboration between governors from both parties to formulate and implement common reading and math standards. The article outlines the new measures that will be integrated into a reformulated Primary and Secondary Education Act, including requirements for states to adopt and certify college and career readiness standards in order to receive Title I funds. The article also mentions funding priorities for states with college and career readiness standards, as well as support for teacher preparation programs and the implementation of assessments aligned with these standards. The article concludes by mentioning additional funding for the Race to the Top program and professional development for teachers and leaders.